## [§](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/#feature-flags)Feature Flags
Feature | Description   
---|---  
`alloc (default)` | Enable features that require use of the heap, RSA in particular.   
`less-safe-getrandom-custom-or-rdrand` | Treat user-provided ("custom") and RDRAND-based `getrandom` implementations as secure random number generators (see `SecureRandom`). This feature only works with `os = "none"` targets. See [ `register_custom_getrandom` ](https://docs.rs/getrandom/0.2.10/getrandom/macro.register_custom_getrandom.html) and [ RDRAND on x86 ](https://docs.rs/getrandom/0.2.10/getrandom/#rdrand-on-x86) for additional details.   
`less-safe-getrandom-espidf` | Treat getrandom as a secure random number generator (see `SecureRandom`) on the esp-idf target. While the esp-idf target does have hardware RNG, it is beyond the scope of ring to ensure its configuration. This feature allows ring to build on esp-idf despite the likelihood that RNG is not secure. This feature only works with `os = espidf` targets. See [ ](https://docs.espressif.com/projects/esp-idf/en/stable/esp32/api-reference/system/random.html)  
`std` | Enable features that use libstd, in particular `std::error::Error` integration. Implies `alloc`.   
`wasm32_unknown_unknown_js` | When this feature is enabled, for the wasm32-unknown-unknown target, Web APIs will be used to implement features like `ring::rand` that require an operating environment of some kind. This has no effect for any other target. This enables the `getrandom` crate's `js` feature.   
## Modules[§](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/#modules)

[aead](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/aead/index.html "mod ring::aead")
    Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data (AEAD).

[agreement](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/agreement/index.html "mod ring::agreement")
    Key Agreement: ECDH, including X25519.

[digest](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/digest/index.html "mod ring::digest")
    SHA-2 and the legacy SHA-1 digest algorithm.

[error](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/error/index.html "mod ring::error")
    Error reporting.

[hkdf](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/hkdf/index.html "mod ring::hkdf")
    HMAC-based Extract-and-Expand Key Derivation Function.

[hmac](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/hmac/index.html "mod ring::hmac")
    HMAC is specified in [RFC 2104](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2104).

[io](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/io/index.html "mod ring::io")
    Serialization and deserialization.

[pbkdf2](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/pbkdf2/index.html "mod ring::pbkdf2")
    PBKDF2 derivation and verification.

[pkcs8](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/pkcs8/index.html "mod ring::pkcs8")
    PKCS#8 is specified in [RFC 5958](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5958).

[rand](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/rand/index.html "mod ring::rand")
    Cryptographic pseudo-random number generation.

[rsa](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/rsa/index.html "mod ring::rsa")
    RSA.

[signature](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/signature/index.html "mod ring::signature")
    Public key signatures: signing and verification.
## Macros[§](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/#macros)

[test_file](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/macro.test_file.html "macro ring::test_file")Deprecated
    References a test input file.

Most of the C and assembly language code in _ring_ comes from BoringSSL. BoringSSL is a fork of OpenSSL. This quote from the BoringSSL README.md discouraging you from using it applies to this project:
> BoringSSL is a fork of OpenSSL that is designed to meet Google's needs.
> Although BoringSSL is an open source project, it is not intended for general use, as OpenSSL is. We don't recommend that third parties depend upon it.
This project was originally shared on GitHub in 2015 as an experiment. It was put on crates.io shortly to help other people with their experiments. It is an experiment.
## Side Channels
See [SIDE-CHANNELS.md](https://github.com/briansmith/ring/blob/2723abbca9e83347d82b056d5b239c6604f786df/SIDE-CHANNELS.md) for important information regarding the limitations of the side channel mitigations in this project.
## Toolchains & Targets
Be especially weary about using toolchains (C compilers, etc.) or targets that aren't supported by other projects, especially BoringSSL. The further you are from using the same version of Clang that Chrome uses, the more weary you should be.
## Bug Reporting
For security vulnerabilities, see <https://github.com/briansmith/ring/security/policy>.
Please report bugs that aren't security vulnerabilities either as pull requests or as issues in [the issue tracker](https://github.com/briansmith/ring/issues).
## Release Notes
It is recommended that you review every commit in this project. Some particularly noteworthy changes are noted in the [RELEASES.md](https://github.com/briansmith/ring/blob/2723abbca9e83347d82b056d5b239c6604f786df/RELEASES.md). We could use some help in making this better.

# Crate ringCopy item path
[Settings](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/settings.html)
[Help](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/help.html)
Summary[Source](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/src/ring/lib.rs.html#15-177)
Expand description
## [§](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/#feature-flags)Feature Flags
Feature | Description   
---|---  
`alloc (default)` | Enable features that require use of the heap, RSA in particular.   
`less-safe-getrandom-custom-or-rdrand` | Treat user-provided ("custom") and RDRAND-based `getrandom` implementations as secure random number generators (see `SecureRandom`). This feature only works with `os = "none"` targets. See [ `register_custom_getrandom` ](https://docs.rs/getrandom/0.2.10/getrandom/macro.register_custom_getrandom.html) and [ RDRAND on x86 ](https://docs.rs/getrandom/0.2.10/getrandom/#rdrand-on-x86) for additional details.   
`less-safe-getrandom-espidf` | Treat getrandom as a secure random number generator (see `SecureRandom`) on the esp-idf target. While the esp-idf target does have hardware RNG, it is beyond the scope of ring to ensure its configuration. This feature allows ring to build on esp-idf despite the likelihood that RNG is not secure. This feature only works with `os = espidf` targets. See [ ](https://docs.espressif.com/projects/esp-idf/en/stable/esp32/api-reference/system/random.html)  
`std` | Enable features that use libstd, in particular `std::error::Error` integration. Implies `alloc`.   
`wasm32_unknown_unknown_js` | When this feature is enabled, for the wasm32-unknown-unknown target, Web APIs will be used to implement features like `ring::rand` that require an operating environment of some kind. This has no effect for any other target. This enables the `getrandom` crate's `js` feature.   
## Modules[§](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/#modules)

[aead](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/aead/index.html "mod ring::aead")
    Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data (AEAD).

[agreement](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/agreement/index.html "mod ring::agreement")
    Key Agreement: ECDH, including X25519.

[digest](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/digest/index.html "mod ring::digest")
    SHA-2 and the legacy SHA-1 digest algorithm.

[error](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/error/index.html "mod ring::error")
    Error reporting.

[hkdf](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/hkdf/index.html "mod ring::hkdf")
    HMAC-based Extract-and-Expand Key Derivation Function.

[hmac](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/hmac/index.html "mod ring::hmac")
    HMAC is specified in [RFC 2104](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2104).

[io](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/io/index.html "mod ring::io")
    Serialization and deserialization.

[pbkdf2](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/pbkdf2/index.html "mod ring::pbkdf2")
    PBKDF2 derivation and verification.

[pkcs8](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/pkcs8/index.html "mod ring::pkcs8")
    PKCS#8 is specified in [RFC 5958](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5958).

[rand](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/rand/index.html "mod ring::rand")
    Cryptographic pseudo-random number generation.

[rsa](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/rsa/index.html "mod ring::rsa")
    RSA.

[signature](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/signature/index.html "mod ring::signature")
    Public key signatures: signing and verification.
## Macros[§](https://docs.rs/ring/latest/ring/#macros)

enriched_crate.readme_summary: The `ring` crate is a high-performance, secure cryptography library for Rust, offering essential cryptographic primitives and utilities. It includes modules for authenticated encryption (AEAD), key agreement (ECDH/X25519), cryptographic hashing (SHA-2/SHA-1), HMAC, HKDF, PBKDF2, RSA, PKCS#8, and cryptographic random number generation. It supports various feature flags for customization across different platforms, including WebAssembly and embedded systems.
enriched_crate.factual_counterfactual:
### Pair 1: Key Agreement  
✅ **Factual:** The `ring` crate supports key agreement protocols such as ECDH, including X25519, through its `agreement` module.  
❌ **Counterfactual:** The `ring` crate supports Diffie-Hellman key exchange using the legacy DH algorithm in its `agreement` module.  

---

### Pair 2: Cryptographic Randomness  
✅ **Factual:** The `ring` crate provides cryptographic pseudo-random number generation via its `rand` module, which can use Web APIs for randomness on the `wasm32-unknown-unknown` target when the `wasm32_unknown_unknown_js` feature is enabled.  
❌ **Counterfactual:** The `ring` crate's `rand` module generates random numbers using a deterministic algorithm, making it unsuitable for cryptographic purposes.  

---

### Pair 3: Hashing Algorithms  
✅ **Factual:** The `ring` crate supports hashing algorithms like SHA-2 and the legacy SHA-1 through its `digest` module.  
❌ **Counterfactual:** The `ring` crate provides support for MD5 hashing in its `digest` module for legacy applications.
